38":"1177–1238","1184–1252":"1184–1252","1240–1285":"1240–1285","–1231":"–1231","–1269":"–1269","1165–1209":"1165–1209","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1165":"1165","1231":"1231","1197":"1197","1186":"1186","1285":"1285","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","1238":"1238","1269":"1269","after 1219":"after 1219","1201":"1201","um 1184":"about 1184","1177":"1177","1209":"1209","1219":"1219","Belgien":"Belgium","Lalaing, France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Nicolas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]},{"name":"Nicolao","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Nicolas I de Lalaing, Seigneur de Lalaing was born as the son of Simon I de Forest de Lalaing, Seigneur de Lalaing and Richesente de Landas. He married Havoise de Marque in 1197. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died after 1219, in France."},"et":{"–after 1219":"–pärast 1219","–1201":"–1201","–1219":"–1219","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1177–1238":"1177–1238","1184–1252":"1184–1252","1240–1285":"1240–1285","–1231":"–1231","–1269":"–1269","1165–1209":"1165–1209","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1165":"1165","1231":"1231","1197":"1197","1186":"1186","1285":"1285","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1184":"1184","1160":"1160","1238":"1238","1269":"1269","after 1219":"pärast 1219","1201":"1201","um 1184":"umbes 1184","1177":"1177","1209":"1209","1219":"1219","Belgien":"Belgia","Lalaing, France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"–after 1219":"–1219 jälkeen","–1201":"–1201","–1219":"–1219","–Female":"Kuol